@startuml ProcLib Startup Handshake - Synchronized Initialization

title ProcLib Startup: Synchronized Process Initialization

participant "Parent Process" as parent
participant "ProcLib" as proclib
participant "Child Process" as child
participant "Child Handler" as handler
participant "Resources\n(DB, Config, etc.)" as resources

== Setup: Parent Calls start_link ==

parent -> proclib: start_link(childInit, childHandler, args)
note right of proclib
  Synchronous call (blocking parent)
  Returns StartResult<T, E>:
  - Ok(childProc)
  - Err(exception)
  Parent waits until child is ready
end note

proclib -> proclib: create CountDownLatch(1)
note right of proclib
  Latch ensures parent blocks
  Child will countdown when ready
end note

== Child Process Spawns ==

proclib -> child: spawn with child initialization
note right of proclib
  Child runs in its own virtual thread
  Parent blocks on latch
end note

child -> child: start virtual thread

parent -> parent: BLOCK on latch.await()
note right of parent
  Parent pauses here
  Waiting for child to call initAck()
end note

== Child Initialization (Async) ==

child -> handler: initialize()
note right of handler
  Child runs initialization code
  Examples:
  - Connect to database
  - Load configuration
  - Initialize resources
  - Perform health checks
end note

handler -> resources: open connections
resources --> handler: success (DB ready)

handler -> handler: load configuration
handler -> handler: verify all resources

note right of handler
  Initialization complete
  Child is fully functional
  Signify to parent: ready!
end note

== Child Acknowledges ==

handler -> proclib: initAck()
note right of proclib
  Child signals: initialization complete
  countDownLatch.countDown()
end note

proclib -> proclib: latch.countDown()

parent -> parent: UNBLOCK from latch.await()
note right of parent
  Parent resumes
  Child guaranteed initialized
  Can now use child
end note

proclib --> parent: return Ok(childProc)

parent -> parent: childProc now ready
parent -> child: send first message
note right of parent
  Can confidently send messages
  Child is fully initialized
  No race conditions
end note

== Failure Case ==

alt Child Initialization Fails

  handler -> handler: exception during init
  handler -> handler: catch exception

  handler -> proclib: initAck(StartResult.Err(exception))

  proclib -> proclib: latch.countDown(exception)

  parent -> parent: UNBLOCK (error)

  proclib --> parent: return Err(exception)

  parent -> parent: handle initialization failure
  note right of parent
    Can:
    1. Retry with different params
    2. Use fallback child
    3. Propagate error upward
    4. Shutdown entire service
  end note

end

== Contrast: Without ProcLib (Fire-and-Forget) ==

note over parent, child
  Without synchronized startup (spawn only):

  parent -> child: spawn(init, handler)
  parent -> child: tell(firstMessage) [IMMEDIATELY]
  parent: continue without waiting

  Problem:
  - Child may not be initialized yet
  - Message arrives during initialization
  - Handler can't access resources (DB not connected)
  - Race condition possible
  - firstMessage lost or causes error

  With ProcLib:
  - Parent blocks on initAck()
  - Child fully initialized before first message
  - No race conditions
  - Initialization failures detected immediately
  - Parent can react intelligently
end note

== Use Cases ==

note right of proclib
  Essential for:

  1. Database Connection Pools
     - Child must connect before serving queries

  2. Configuration Loading
     - Child must load config before starting

  3. Service Dependencies
     - Child depends on parent being up

  4. Health Checks
     - Child must verify health before accepting traffic

  5. Warm-up / Cache Initialization
     - Child must pre-populate cache before serving

  6. Dependent Service Startup
     - Service A must start before Service B
     - B's initAck() waits for A fully online
end note

== Exception Propagation ==

note right of proclib
  Erlang's proc_lib:start_link/3 pattern:

  Ensures caller knows:
  1. When child successfully initialized
  2. Why child failed (exception details)
  3. Can respond immediately (no timeouts/guessing)

  Parent can then:
  - Coordinate across service boundaries
  - Build reliable startup sequences
  - Handle failures early (fail-fast)
  - Avoid partial/zombie processes
end note
